  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. U.S. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting thresholds for cash transactions\n- Criminalize knowingly engaging in financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n- Impose significant penalties and potential criminal charges\n\n3. International Frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice\n- Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC)\n\nThese statutes aim to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities by establishing legal frameworks, reporting requirements, and penalties for individuals and institutions involved in such transactions.",
